<title>&lt;html&gt;
  &lt;head&gt;
    
  &lt;/head&gt;
  &lt;body&gt;
    &lt;table border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;5&quot; cellspacing=&quot;5&quot;&gt;
      &lt;tr&gt;
        &lt;td&gt;
          &lt;font face=&quot;Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif&quot;&gt;Molecules are 
          created when covalent bonds bind a group of atoms together. The 
          covalent bond, which is a sharing of electrons between two atoms, is 
          often represented as a stick (the bond) connecting two balls (the 
          atoms). The sharing of electrons can also be depicted by coloring 
          the &amp;quot;surface&amp;quot; of a molecule to show how the electrons are 
          distributed.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Depending on how the electrons are shared in the 
          bond, polar covalent and non-polar covalent bonds are formed. A 
          non-polar covalent bond is formed when electrons are shared equally 
          (or almost equally), and a polar covalent bond is formed when 
          electrons are somewhat unevenly shared. If electrons are unevenly 
          shared, a partial positive and negative charge can occur, as you can 
          see by the colors shown on the water molecule.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Covalent bonds 
          are 100 to 1000 times stronger than the inter-molecular attractions 
          which cause molecules to stick together.&lt;/font&gt;
        &lt;/td&gt;
        &lt;td&gt;
          &lt;img width=&quot;365&quot; src=&quot;covalentBonds.png&quot; height=&quot;316&quot;&gt;
          
        &lt;/td&gt;
      &lt;/tr&gt;
    &lt;/table&gt;
    &lt;table border=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;5&quot; cellspacing=&quot;5&quot;&gt;
      &lt;tr&gt;
        &lt;td&gt;
          &lt;img width=&quot;281&quot; src=&quot;weakBonds.png&quot; height=&quot;343&quot;&gt;
          
        &lt;/td&gt;
        &lt;td&gt;
          &lt;p&gt;
            &lt;font face=&quot;Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif&quot;&gt;The weak 
            attractions between molecules are called &lt;strong&gt;van der Waals 
            attractions&lt;/strong&gt;, and can be divided into two categories: &lt;strong&gt;dipole-dipole&lt;/strong&gt; 
            attractions and &lt;strong&gt;London Dispersion &lt;/strong&gt;attractions. &lt;/font&gt;
          &lt;/p&gt;
          &lt;blockquote&gt;
            &lt;p&gt;
              &lt;strong&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif&quot;&gt;Dipole-dipole 
              attractions: &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif&quot;&gt;When 
              a molecule has at least one polar covalent bond, its partial 
              positive region can attract to the partial negative region of 
              another polar molecule. If a partially positive hydrogen from 
              one molecule attracts to the partially negative part of another 
              molecule, we call this polar attraction a &amp;quot;hydrogen bond&amp;quot;. This 
              type of intermolecular attraction is common in biologically 
              important molecules. &lt;/font&gt;
            &lt;/p&gt;
            &lt;p&gt;
              &lt;strong&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif&quot;&gt;London 
              dispersion attractions:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif&quot;&gt; 
              Even if a molecule does not have partially positive and negative 
              parts, it can still feel a slight attraction for other 
              molecules. This attraction is due to the random movement of 
              electrons which can result in a brief, flickering polarity. This 
              attraction is even weaker than the weak dipole-dipole 
              attractions that occur with permanently polar molecules. &lt;/font&gt;
            &lt;/p&gt;
          &lt;/blockquote&gt;
        &lt;/td&gt;
      &lt;/tr&gt;
    &lt;/table&gt;
  &lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;
</title>
